Britain, and what's next?
NEW YORK – It will take a lot of time for Britain, Europe, and the whole world to digest the implications of the referendum on the 'Brexit' led by the United Kingdom.
The most profound consequences will, of course, depend on the European Union's response to the United Kingdom's withdrawal.
Most people initially believed that the EU would not 'cut off the branch it was sitting on': after all, an amicable divorce seemed to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce – as is often the case – could become complicated.
The benefits of commercial and economic integration between the United Kingdom and the EU are reciprocal, and if the EU seriously takes its conviction that more economic integration is desirable, its leaders would strive to ensure that the links remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
However, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance schemes in favor of Luxembourg companies and now European Commission president, seems to adopt a hard line: 'Out means out,' he declared.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be held responsible for presiding over the first step of the EU's dissolution.
He argues that, in order to dissuade other countries from leaving, the EU should not accept any compromises, offering the United Kingdom barely more than what the World Trade Organization agreements guarantee to it.
In other words, Europe should not be kept united by the benefits it offers its members, which far exceed its costs.
Prosperity, a sense of solidarity, and the pride of being European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, Europe should be maintained by threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position does not take into account a lesson that is clearly apparent, both in the vote in favor of Brexit and in the primaries of the Republican Party in the United States: a large part of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the past four decades may have been good for the top 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had long predicted that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
This day has finally arrived.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider that commercial agreements are the source of their misfortunes.
Although this is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's commercial agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of corporate interests but complete exclusion of ordinary citizens or workers.
Without surprise, the results have been one-way: the workers' negotiating position has weakened even further, thus exacerbating the effects of the laws that diminish the weight of unions and the rights of employees.
Although commercial agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to shifting the political balance towards capital.
The rules of intellectual property, for example, have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise prices.
However, any increase in the market power of enterprises de facto involves a decrease in real wages – an increase in inequalities that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is increasing – and the same is true for market power.
The effects of stagnation and decrease in real wages have been added to those of austerity, which has threatened compressions in public services that are dependent on so many low- and middle-income workers.
The economic uncertainty that results for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for all, but especially for former colonial powers.
And yet, although many would probably deny it, an increase in the supply of unskilled labor leads – as long as we are in the presence of normal negative-sloping demand curves – to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot fall, unemployment increases.
This is especially worrisome in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high global unemployment rate.
Europe, especially the euro zone, has been very poorly managed over the past decades, to the point that its average unemployment rate is now in two digits.
Unrestricted migration in Europe means that countries that have better succeeded in reducing unemployment will ultimately, predictably, end up welcoming more than their fair share of refugees.
The workers in these countries bear the cost of depressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from a better labor market.
The burden of refugees, unsurprisingly, is borne by those who are least able to do so.
Of course, there's a lot of talk about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed benefits - social protection, education, healthcare etc. - to all its citizens, this may be the case.
But, for countries that provide a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and compressions in public services has been the evisceration of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Working-class and middle-class households have not benefited from economic growth.
They realize that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but they then saw billions affected in saving the banks, and insignificant amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the real median income (corrected for inflation) for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the electorate's anger should not come as a surprise.
Furthermore, the politicians who promised change have not met expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew that the system was unjust, but they started seeing it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thus losing what little confidence they still had in the traditional politicians' ability or willingness to correct it.
This too is understandable: new politicians shared the perspectives of those who promised that globalization would be beneficial to all.
However, a vote of anger does not solve the problems, and may on the contrary lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
It's the same if one responds to a vote with anger.
Forgiving the past is a basic principle in economics.
From both sides of the Channel, politics must now strive to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment was able to do so little to respond to the concerns of many citizens.
Each EU government must now consider the improvement of the well-being of ordinary citizens as its main objective.
More neoliberal ideology will not help.
And we should stop confusing goals and means: for example, free trade, if well managed, could bring about greater shared prosperity; but if poorly managed, it will certainly reduce the standard of living of many – perhaps the majority – of citizens.
There are alternatives to the current neoliberal arrangements that can create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives – such as the proposed Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership with the EU by US President Barack Obama – that would cause much more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past, in order to adopt the former and avoid the latter.
